pageTitle: S'pore home prices to rise 8% by 2017: study - Yahoo Singapore Finance
title: Currencies
TableContextTimeStampBeforeTable: {15084="Contrary to the view of many, our analysis shows that prices will only correct marginally by 2017, if the government pushes out the supply of property as aggressively as it has over the last three years through its Government Land Sales (GLS) programme," said Michael Wan, Analyst at Credit Suisse., 19347=Tue, Aug 4, 2015, 9:56 PM SGT - Singapore Markets closed, 14465=If the government continued to release land at the rate of 16,000 units each year, home prices will drop by around one percent in 2017, an indication that a supply glut will most likely not occur., 15443=By Romesh Navaratnarajah:A number of analysts have predicted a drop in Singapore's home prices due to a large supply of land coming onstream and tighter monetary policy from the US Federal Reserve. But a study by Credit Suisse that was reported in The Business Times predicts that prices will rise some eight percent by 2017.}
